> Fun fact! Did you know that al pastor tacos were originally a mash-up of Middle Eastern shawarma spices and Mexican cuisine? Here, our chefs' take on the traditional street food gives the dish an extra-quick twist by using spiced pulled pork. Plus, no taco would be complete without salsa: This one is studded with pineapple, tomato, and onion. In just 15 minutes, you'll be ready to bite right in!

Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced); mince a few slices until you have 2 TBSP (4 TBSP for 4 servings). Drain @pineapple{4%oz} over a small #bowl{}, reserving juice; roughly chop. Finely dice @roma tomato{1}(diced finely). Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}(finely chopped). Quarter @lime{1}(quartered).

Heat @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until just softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add another drizzle of oil, then add @ground turkey{10%oz}, @southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}, pineapple juice, half the @Tex-Mex paste{1}(half reserved for 4 servings), @sugar{1/2%tsp}(1 tsp for 4), salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until turkey is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Simply cook through this step as instructed, swapping in turkey for pork.

Turn off heat.

While filling cooks, in a second small bowl, combine minced onion, chopped pineapple, tomato, cilantro, and a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Season with salt and pepper.

Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates; fill with turkey filling and pineapple salsa. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.